Hello. I have a question about cookies, and what amounts to cross site cooking. I have a server with a number of virtual domains. The same server has only one SSL domain name. When I create a cookie for the virtual domain, can I create an identical cookie for the secure domain as well? Could I do this with a 3rd party cookie? Or possible an embedded frame that accesses the ssl domain and creates another cookie?

KevinBooks: if all sites share the same certificate (which is a difficult situation) you can create multiple SSL virtual domains too. KevinBooks: anyhow the obvious simple solution is to send each cookie twice, once with a domain and the other with the other domain. Fifoxez: it means that you are telling the server you only accept stuff that the server is not configured to serve. Seems pretty obvious to me. Fifoxez: so change the server or change the range of things your app is prepared to accept. aao_pwner: and thats exactly is not clear in ´You're speaking plain HTTP to an SSL-enabled server portª?

I have an apache running with suexec module. this module has been compiled with uidmin 100. however, I have a cgi script here which I *definitely* need to run as wwwrun (which is uid 8). is there any way to do this apart from disabling suexec completely (suexec is needed for other sites)? this paranoia that's going on today is probably costing people 90% of their time fixing stuff... wonderful how such security measures make php and cgi incompatible to each other. is it possible to change the minimum uid for suexec WITHOUT recompiling all of apache? mooney2: but, it's a loadable module... not sure if I can recompile just a single module? hmmmmm.... LoadModule suexec_module                  /usr/lib64/apache2-prefork/mod_suexec.so are you sure? mooney2: i would recompile apache, but this is a production system with lots of sites and I can't afford to take half of them down potentially ;) (if thinkgs break) mooney2: yes, I also only knew of the seperate suexec binary but this indeed seems to be a module mooney2: 'test seperately' a dozen highly complex sites? heh it took me two days to get all sites running again and testing, i don't want to repeat again :) if I knew where in the .so the minimum uid is stored, i'd just use a damn hex editor. mooney2: hmmmmmm... really? and that works? :) then let me fetch the apache sources and try. mooney2: well, normally you tell it to configure when compiling apache itself... --with-suexec-minuid or something mooney2: well, if it's checked in the support program, it would be much easier, because then I could just recompile that. well, does anyone here know then if apache2 uses an external suexec binary? (if something like "LoadModule suexec_module                  /usr/lib64/apache2-prefork/mod_suexec.so" is present)? oh, wait... argh [Fri Sep 22 22:51:14 2006] [notice] suEXEC mechanism enabled (wrapper: /usr/sbin/suexec2) that really looks as if it IS external. hehe well, but the uid restriction could still be in the module, not the binary. because it's also passed as a ./configure option to apache... that's odd on the other hand, there is no minuid or even min to be found in neither the .c nor the .h file.

I looked at a few of those and they generally didn't look detectable from the page context alone whether it has a positive effect on attitudes depends on the outcome doing enough work to predict the outcome but not actually make any changes would not really be acting in good faith though, I think I think there is a sense from some quarters that any feature that is nominally "for accessibility" is absolutely needed, regardless of whether it does anything to help accessibility in practice and that even trying to study the question of whether it helps accessibility in practice is somehow illegitimate notwithstanding what I think of specific features, it is hard to make a good spec when there are sacred cows that may not be examined critically, so I don't know how much we can accomodate that point of view I know you don't - I'm just saying it's hard to collaborate with someone who does have sacred cows, even if you happen to agree with them on one point I do think Chaals made a good point that accessibility features might deserve special status even if only a subset of especially accessible sites use them (properly), since those might be the only sites that someone with a given disability can use at all but I don't know if the evidence bears that out as a justification for headers="" or the like it would require examples of actual particularly accessible sites that consistently use it in a way that is beneficial not just a theory that there might be some 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: one thing that might work is to limit the number of access keys and make it a set that UAs can map in a natural way on each platform to something w/ no conflicts 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: if the set was 0-9 for instance, it could be unmodified 0-9 on phones with a keypad, Cmd-0 - Cmd-9 on Macs, Ctrl-0 - Ctrl-9 on windows, etc (assuming those are actually free) but I'm not sure how you address discoverability I think the page has to provide info about shortcuts that's how keyboard shortcuts work in native apps they are listed in the menu bar having a shortcut list with labels somewhere in the page or accessible from the chrome would be the natural analogy I'm not sure if styling them to mention they key helps thee UA could do a better job if it is the only thing that knows the concrete key mapping, but you need a label to go next to the shortcut *the UA it could even be a menu or submenu in the menu bar "Page Shorcuts" 6905646aa63b96d6bdfbd256603fa58e: if the modifier is a commonly used one on the OS, that could be distracting something based on <command> seems like a good basic approach the idea is that a shorcut key actually activates a command, for which there might also be one or more UI elements it makes more sense to associate it with a command, which can then have an appropriate label 6905646aa63b96d6bdfbd256603fa58e: example? (I don't know of dialog windows that have keyboard shortcuts beyond the standard tab/enter/esc and such) I don't think that is standard usually in OS X all the keyboard shorcuts also have a menu item, so you can look in the menu system to see the shortcuts Windows is different since it uses the underline system sometimes, and that may apply both to menus and items in a dialog

so it's not exactly right to say "For something to become part of the HTML WG's recommendation it has to be in use." on the other hand, there is a presumption that features from existing specs that are almost never used or almost always used wrong are probably flawed sure it's a different kind of evidence obviously we do have things in the spec that aren't in use personally I don't see what profile gets you that you couldn't put in a <meta> or <link> tag, for something like GRDDL and for microformats profile is clearly unhelpful and indeed useless there are so few GRDDL users that inconveniencing them is irrelevant what exactly does wordpress do with the profile attribute anyway? I couldn't find it on the few wordpress blogs I looked at GRDDL requires the document to have more markup in the document than just the profile attribute, right? it has to be, first of all, the GRDDL profile, not the relevant microformat profile(s) and then a <link rel="transformation" ...> to the GRDDL xsl stylesheet http://www.w3.org/2004/01/rdxh/spec#grddl-xhtml if I'm reading this right the profile attribute says that rel="transformation" should be interpreted as a GRDDL transformation it doesn't say anything about what microformats you use and afaict GRDDL doesn't care about that but I could be misunderstanding this although one of them links to GRDDL transforms for FOAF, CC and Geo, without profile markup for any of those so yeah, the idea of GRDDL is that your document's data can only be extracted by GRDDL-aware processors if you have marked it up in several GRDDL-specific ways, the most relevant ones not being the profile attribute XSLT requires use of XPath as well, so you have at least three problems IBM has a /8 , does Japan really have less than that? b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: Interesting indeed. Ah, didn't realize Lauren Wood was his wife. Hm, the newest "let's hash <input type=password>" suggestion seems pretty decent. (Except for suggesting sending the extra information in a header instead of an extra form input.) Heh, indeed. will put that in his response email, as it's good snark (and a good point). Possible disadvantage - a good server uses a good crypto hash, which is slow to evaluate, forcing each login attempt to take a non-trivial amount of time.  If the attacker can use their own resources to compute the cryptographic hash quickly relative to the attempts (frex, putting several machines to work hashing for each one making requests), they can bypass that. But then, those are machines not being spent making requests, so that may end up being a wash. I wasn't meaning to distribute the individual hashings, but to have several machines hashing for each machine making requests. Yes. But requests are faster than hashing with a good hash. (The full rtt may not be, but you don't have to worry about that.) Yes, that's the contexty. s/y// Then you've dropped down to the same rate that you'd get if the server was computing the hash itself. But like I said, it sounds like it'd be a wash anyway. Or rather, it sounds like it's exactly identical, except with useless message-passing. Yes.

It's not sane to distribute the actual hash computation, when you're doing brute-force hashing. Just have each node compute its own hash, it's embarrassingly parallel. Doesn't each request only submit one hash? Well, "good" for password storage, anyway. Why wouldn't you just have each node both hash and submit at the same time? Submitting should take negligible CPU time. Compared to hashing. It doesn't make sense to forward the hashes to other nodes to submit. looks at the thread Right, that's what I meant.

69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: does HTML5 specify "cut", "copy", "paste" and "beforepaste" events? 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: shouldn't "cut", "copy", "paste" and "beforepaste" be required for implementations at least, for compatibility with existing content? 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: also, even if it makes sense to say everything draggable should be copyable, I don't think it makes sense to require that every time in the UI you can use the Copy command, you can also drag that's not how native UIs work 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: how about via the copy/paste events that browsers already support and which are used by content? 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: I don't see how that conclusion follows - one could certainly support copy/paste events while making drag/drop events also work via the copy/paste UI 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: in fact, that is what browsers will have to do anyway if they implement the HTML5 spec as written and choose not to break existing content 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: so it would be nice if there was a spec that describes how it works 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: you have to specify how they are sequenced with drag/drop events, if both occur in a copy/paste sequence - seems hard to do in a separate spec it's a potential interop problem for implementing what the spec says for drag/drop events (though I don't know if implementations will actually be willing to hook up drag & drop events to the copy/paste UI) anyway I'll send email or file a bug or something I do believe there is significant content using the copy/paste events, but I don't have a quantitative study at hand

And then 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6 and I have been seriously discussing aligning CSS and SVG's notions of gradients, so it's possible that further changes may arrive in the near future. (We should see something about that on the www-style list soon.) a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: Yeah, issue 179 is actually impossible!  Turns out that several of the radial gradients can't be reproduced in SVG. Yeah, which is why we're planning on aligning our abstractions so that we can express the same things using roughly the same concepts. Eh, it just means that we need to lift SVG a bit, because I think the cases that it's not hitting are useful. That latter part is due to SVG having a slightly crazy notion of image servers that isn't sufficiently developed and general, while CSS doesn't have such an idea at all and has so far relied on url() images all working basically the same. I want to both generalize SVG's image-server concept, and upgrade CSS to also use it. Also: omg I'm stopping reading all the issue-76 threads.  They are entirely uninteresting.  >_< Also: now I need to go write a change proposal for that one dt/dd issue.  Not a counter-proposal, at least. np. a3f19f90edf0a0893c7847d08016abe3: actually no, the common case is that the interfaces are only visible to global objects that implement WindowBrowsingContext pretty much nothing (only ECMA262-defined types) are visible to the "empty" global object, for instance http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/multipage/browsers.html#script0 and http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/multipage/browsers.html#the-javascript paragraph 3 there's an open bug on figuring out what it means exactly global objects are very complex since the global object has to change when you navigate, but there's only one Window object per window so you get pschyzophrenic code the global object is the same, but the 'window' attribute on that global object no longer points to the global object, even though the value it used to have is === the value that it had when it _was_ equal to the global object the web is a crazy crazy platform basically the Window object reflects the properties of the global object of the active document and you can never get a pointer to the actual global object as i understand it well right now none of this is defined but yeah it is the 'this' is not the actual global object, it turns out but an object pretending to be it as i understand it see also http://www.w3.org/Bugs/Public/show_bug.cgi?id=5850 q.v. topic :-) dunno, haven't figured it out yet thanks later

The cannot or the can? 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: I doubt accessibility is the major driver for XBL2 adoption, so I doubt that's the case. 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: Custom widgets are too complicated to implement by most authors full stop.
